<h2>Why CLI + AI?</h2>

<p>
  Every developer has repetitive GitHub tasks they hate: writing PR descriptions that explain what changed, labeling issues correctly, drafting release notes from a pile of commits. These tasks are annoying because they require <em>reading and summarizing</em> — something AI is exceptionally good at.
</p>

<p>
  I built <strong>gh-auto</strong>, a CLI tool with three commands that automate the drudgery:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><code>gh-auto pr-describe</code> — Reads a PR's diff and generates a clear description</li>
  <li><code>gh-auto label-issues</code> — Analyzes issue text and applies the right labels</li>
  <li><code>gh-auto release-notes</code> — Generates release notes from commits between tags</li>
</ul>

<h2>Design Principles</h2>

<p>
  I had three rules going in:
</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Dry-run by default mentality</strong> — Every command supports <code>--dry-run</code>. You can always preview what the AI would do before it touches your repo.</li>
  <li><strong>Composable with existing workflows</strong> — Output is pipe-friendly. You can use it in GitHub Actions, shell scripts, or just the terminal.</li>
  <li><strong>Minimal dependencies</strong> — Commander for CLI parsing, Octokit for GitHub API, Anthropic SDK for AI. Nothing else.</li>
</ol>

<h2>How PR Description Generation Works</h2>

<p>
  The most useful command. Here's the flow:
</p>

<pre><code set:html={`// 1. Fetch the PR diff from GitHub API
const diff = await github.getPRDiff(repo, number);

// 2. Build a focused prompt
const prompt = \`Analyze this pull request diff and write a clear,
  concise description. Include: what changed, why, and any
  notable implementation details.

  Diff:
  \${diff}\`;

// 3. Send to Claude with a system prompt that enforces format
const description = await ai.generate(prompt, {
  system: "You are a senior engineer writing PR descriptions...",
});

// 4. Either preview or update the PR
if (dryRun) {
  console.log(description);
} else {
  await github.updatePR(repo, number, { body: description });
}`} /></pre>

<p>
  The key to good output is the <strong>system prompt</strong>. I spent more time tuning the system prompts than writing the actual CLI code. For PR descriptions, I instruct the AI to:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>Start with a one-line summary</li>
  <li>Group changes by area (backend, frontend, config)</li>
  <li>Call out breaking changes or things reviewers should focus on</li>
  <li>Keep it under 300 words — no one reads a novel in a PR description</li>
</ul>

<h2>Issue Labeling: Classification as a Service</h2>

<p>
  Issue labeling is a classification problem. The AI reads the issue title and body, then selects from your repo's existing labels. It's not generating labels — it's picking from a known set, which makes it much more reliable.
</p>

<pre><code set:html={`// Fetch the repo's label set
const labels = await github.listLabels(repo);
const labelNames = labels.map(l =&gt; l.name);

// Ask AI to classify
const prompt = \`Given these available labels: \${labelNames.join(", ")}

  Classify this issue: "\${issue.title}"
  Body: \${issue.body}

  Return ONLY the label names that apply, comma-separated.\`;`} /></pre>

<p>
  Constraining the AI's output to a known set is a pattern I use everywhere. It dramatically reduces hallucination and makes the output parseable.
</p>

<h2>What Made This Project Work</h2>

<p>
  <strong>The AI isn't the product — the automation is.</strong> The CLI would be useful even with template-based generation. AI just makes the output significantly better. This mindset keeps the tool grounded: if the AI API is down, the tool still works with sensible fallbacks.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Prompt engineering is real engineering.</strong> Each command has a carefully crafted system prompt with few-shot examples, format constraints, and explicit instructions about what to include and omit. The prompts are the most valuable code in the project.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Every command is stateless.</strong> No databases, no config files, no login flows. Just environment variables for API keys and command-line flags for everything else. This makes it trivial to use in CI/CD.
</p>

<h2>Using It in GitHub Actions</h2>

<pre><code set:html={`# .github/workflows/auto-pr.yml
on:
  pull_request:
    types: [opened]

jobs:
  describe:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
      - run: npx gh-auto pr-describe --repo $REPO --number $PR_NUMBER
        env:
          GITHUB_TOKEN: \${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }}
          ANTHROPIC_API_KEY: \${{ secrets.ANTHROPIC_API_KEY }}`} /></pre>

<p>
  Three lines of YAML and every PR gets an auto-generated description. That's the kind of automation that compounds over time.
</p>

